"Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease","Liver cirrhosis","Obesity","Vitamin D deficiency"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic thromboembolic disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an important and potentially curable cause of pulmonary hypertension that occurs in up to 4% of patients following acute pulmonary embolism. It should be considered in all cases of unexplained pulmonary hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastro-oesophageal reflux disease\u003C/strong\u003E affects the lower oesophageal sphincter and does not cause pulmonary hypertension. \u003Cstrong\u003ELiver cirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause portal hypertension but does not typically cause pulmonary hypertension. \u003Cstrong\u003EObesity\u003C/strong\u003E may contribute to sleep apnoea which can lead to pulmonary hypertension, but is not a direct cause. \u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects bone metabolism and does not cause pulmonary hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVentilation-perfusion scanning is the preferred screening test for chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension as it is sensitive and non-invasive.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension occurs in up to 4% of patients after acute pulmonary embolism","Chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension should be considered in all cases of unexplained pulmonary hypertension","Ventilation-perfusion scanning is the preferred screening test for chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension"],"references":["Kim NH, Delcroix M, Jais X, Madani MM, Matsubara H, Mayer E, Ogo T, Tapson VF, Ghofrani HA, Jenkins DP. Chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension. Eur Respir J. 2019 Jan 24;53(1):1801915. doi: 10.1183/13993003.01915-2018. PMID: 30545969; PMCID: PMC6351341.","Hoeper MM, Madani MM, Nakanishi N, Meyer B, Cebotari S, Rubin LJ. Chronic thromboembolic pulmona